Situation1: They occasionally participate in family traditions during holidays and gatherings.
Expectation2: Meet sales targets set by management
Situation2: On the final day of the quarter, the team must hit the cumulative target to avoid penalties and secure bonuses.
Story: I stared at my phone, the screen flashing with reminders from my manager: “Final push! We need five more sales to hit target!” My headset felt heavier than usual, pressing into my temples as I dialed another number. My heart pounded, not just from the pressure at work, but from the text I’d just received from Mom: “Dinner starts at 6. Don’t be late. Grandma made your favorite.” It was the last night of the quarter, and every call counted. But tonight was also the family’s annual holiday dinner, a tradition I’d never missed. I could already picture the table, the laughter, the stories, and the look of disappointment on my parents’ faces if I didn’t show. My manager’s voice echoed in my mind, reminding me of the team’s reliance on me, while my mother’s gentle words tugged at my heart. I glanced at the clock, feeling the weight of both worlds pressing in, each demanding my presence, each unwilling to wait.
